title: #178 fix input data
Proposal for relaxed data constraint in non WS-* serviceTask
body:
This statement is made for service tasks on p158 (PDF p.188): 

```
         "In addition the following constraints are introduced 
         when the Service Task references an Operation: The Service Task has 
         exactly one inputSet and at most one outputSet. It has a single Data 
         Input with an ItemDefinition equivalent to the one defined by the 
         Message referenced by the inMessageRef attribute of the associated 
         Operation. If the Operation defines output Messages, the Service Task 
         has a single Data Output that has an ItemDefinition equivalent to the 
         one defined by the Message referenced by the outMessageRef attribute 
         of the associated Operation."
```

For RESTful implementations it turns out this is an unnecessary constraint so in order to minimise the burden for such implementations we propose the following change to the text: 

After 
```   
         "...when the Service Task references an Operation: ..." 
```
add 
```
         " and when the implementation attribute of the Service Task is set to '##WebService'"
```

title: Minimal specification of serviceTask for 'ping' style use case
body:
In light of the following quote: 
```
    p213 (PDF p243) [An ioSpec contains] An optional reference to 
    the Data Inputs of the InputOutputSpecification. If the 
    InputOutputSpecification defines no Data Input, it means no 
    data is REQUIRED to start the Activity. This is an ordered set.
```
I propose removal of the dataInput which is consistent with the WSDL I produced. As well as the matching inputSet/dataInputRef  

That would leave the serviceTask in test A.1.1 like this: 
```
        <semantic:serviceTask implementation="##WebService" completionQuantity="1" isForCompensation="false" startQuantity="1" name="Task 2" id="task2" operationRef="operation1">
            <semantic:incoming>_1a66ccd9-a80c-44bc-a06f-a684b8370443</semantic:incoming>
            <semantic:outgoing>_725826e9-0e8b-4cb4-842b-e0279515d821</semantic:outgoing>
            <semantic:ioSpecification>
              <semantic:inputSet/>
              <semantic:outputSet/>
            </semantic:ioSpecification>
        </semantic:serviceTask>
```

title: dataOutputAssociation from startDataOutput to taskDataInput
body:
### A.1.2 reference visualization
![15cb0d1e-db7e-11e3-8de3-aff1969b665e](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/5450234/3029638/867caf8c-e037-11e3-8242-5493208d08c8.png)

### A.1.2 reference serialization
StartEvent (I omitted parts, just to focus on the problem)
```xml
<semantic:startEvent name="Start Event" id="startEvent">
    ...
    <semantic:dataOutput name="Start Event Data Output" id="startEventDataOutput" itemSubjectRef="serviceInput" />
    <semantic:dataOutputAssociation id="startEventDataOutputAssociation">
        <semantic:sourceRef>startEventDataOutput</semantic:sourceRef>
        <semantic:targetRef>dataInputTask1</semantic:targetRef>
    </semantic:dataOutputAssociation>
    <semantic:outputSet>
        <semantic:dataOutputRefs>startEventDataOutput</semantic:dataOutputRefs>
    </semantic:outputSet>
    ...
</semantic:startEvent>
```
UserTask
```xml
<semantic:userTask implementation="##unspecified" name="Task 1" id="task1" startQuantity="1" isForCompensation="false" completionQuantity="1">
    ...
    <semantic:ioSpecification>
        <semantic:dataInput name="Data Input Task 1" id="dataInputTask1" itemSubjectRef="serviceInput" />
        ...
        <semantic:inputSet>
            <semantic:dataInputRefs>dataInputTask1</semantic:dataInputRefs>
        </semantic:inputSet>
        ...
    </semantic:ioSpecification>
    ...
</semantic:userTask>
```

### Problem
Please correct me if I am wrong. In a DataOutputAssociation the targetRef has to reference to an itemAwareElement in the current scope of the process. The *dataInputTask1* is the dataInput of the UserTask. During the execution of the *startEventDataOutputAssociation* the UserTask is not in the current scope of the process, it has not yet received the execution token. So it is not possible to have the dataInput of the task as targetRef of the dataOutputAssociation of the startEvent.

### Proposed solution
Add a dataObject in the process to transfer the content of the message from the startEvent to the task.
*Technically*
- add a dataObject in the process
- edit the current startDataOutputAssociation targetRef to reference the dataObject
- add a userTaskDataInputAssociation with sourceRef referencing the dataObject and targetRef referencing the userTaskDataInput.

### Correlated Problem
Symmetrically, this issue affect also the UserTask that is connected to the endEvent.

title: targetRef referencing a dataOutput instead of a dataInput
body:
### A.1.2 reference visualization

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/4007840/2973472/15cb0d1e-db7e-11e3-8de3-aff1969b665e.png)


### A.1.2 reference serialization

```xml
<semantic:userTask implementation="##unspecified" completionQuantity="1" isForCompensation="false" startQuantity="1" name="Task 3" id="task3">
	<semantic:incoming>_725826e9-0e8b-4cb4-842b-e0279515d821</semantic:incoming>
	<semantic:outgoing>_737085c4-8771-41e9-b30e-fa2668d0a481</semantic:outgoing>
	<semantic:ioSpecification>
		<semantic:dataInput id="dataInputTask3" name="Data Input Task 3" itemSubjectRef="serviceOutput"/>
		<semantic:dataOutput id="dataOutputTask3" name="Data Output Task 3" itemSubjectRef="serviceOutput"/>
		<semantic:inputSet>
			<semantic:dataInputRefs>dataInputTask3</semantic:dataInputRefs>
		</semantic:inputSet>
		<semantic:outputSet>
			<semantic:dataOutputRefs>dataOutputTask3</semantic:dataOutputRefs>
		</semantic:outputSet>
	</semantic:ioSpecification>
	<semantic:dataInputAssociation id="dataInputAssociationTask3">
		<semantic:sourceRef>dataObjectRef2</semantic:sourceRef>
		<semantic:targetRef>dataOutputTask3</semantic:targetRef>
	</semantic:dataInputAssociation>
	<semantic:dataOutputAssociation id="dataOutputAssociationTask3">
		<semantic:sourceRef>dataOutputTask3</semantic:sourceRef>
		<semantic:targetRef>endEventDataInput</semantic:targetRef>			
	</semantic:dataOutputAssociation>
	<semantic:performer>
		<semantic:resourceRef>resource_Performer_2</semantic:resourceRef>
	</semantic:performer>
</semantic:userTask>
```


### Problem

The *targetRef* of *dataInputAssociationTask3* points to *dataOutputTask*. This is surprising, as **DataInputAssociations** are used to populate **DataInputs** (cf. table 10.3 on page 152 of the spec). Yet the *dataInputAssociationTask3* targets a **DataOutput**.

### Proposed resolution

Replace the value *dataOutputTask3* of the *targetRef* element with *dataInputTask3*.

title: Connecting a Message via an association to a MessageFlow?
body:
I got a question regarding a special modelling style. The question is how do you connect the message decorator to a message flow correctly. 

First option would be to put it directly on the message flow as shown in the BPMN 2.0 spec on page 411 (see MessageFlow_V1 below)

Second option would be to connect the Message decorator via an undirected association to the message flow (see MessageFlow_V2 below). 

I am wondering now if the MessageFlow_V2 example is actually valid BPMN 2.0 and interchangeable with the XML serialization.

From my point of view it is no valid BPMN 2.0 as Message is no FlowElement and therefore cannot be referenced by the BPMNShape element in the BPMNDI part which makes it impossible to place the Message decorator to any arbitrary position as done in MessageFlow_V2.

Additionally there is no BPMNShape listed in the spec for the single message symbol (table 12.35 on page 411). Sections BPMNShape (Section 12.3.2) and BPMNEdge (Section 12.3.3) also supports this. So I would say the meta model of BPMN 2.0 does not support this.

MessageFlow_V1: Message Flow with Message decorator
![message association v1](https://f.cloud.github.com/assets/3901085/1296823/8604011e-30d2-11e3-9cbf-835453a08d74.png)

MessageFlow_V2: Message Flow with Message decorator connected via association
![message association v2](https://f.cloud.github.com/assets/3901085/1296822/860353cc-30d2-11e3-9246-fb6122b51c85.png)

title: Add results for A.4.1 and new camunda-bpmn.js renderer
[Reference] [B.1.0] [B.2.0] Odd spaces in identifiers
body:
The new B.1.0 and B.2.0 tests introduced a regression: The name attribute values of elements often have odd spaces.
E.g., ``` name="Collapsed Sub- Process 1 Multi- Instances "``` in the following BPMN file.

**Link to B.2.0.bpmn**:
[Link](https://github.com/bpmn-miwg/bpmn-miwg-test-suite/blob/master/B%20-%20Validate%20that%20tool%20covers%20conformance%20class%20set/Reference/B.2.0.bpmn)

**Excerpt from B.2.0.bpmn**:
```xml
        <semantic:parallelGateway gatewayDirection="Unspecified" name="Parallel Gateway 2 " id="_397c783e-ad6a-4cf3-8266-9b41962c83bd">
            <semantic:incoming>_8321494b-9c3c-483a-b4d2-79e6254211c0</semantic:incoming>
            <semantic:incoming>_b41b9c86-bc41-4b6e-ac32-70e1342e6128</semantic:incoming>
            <semantic:incoming>_de249cbe-d431-4e1f-bc8c-a90aec438683</semantic:incoming>
            <semantic:outgoing>_2752e07c-f2e4-4384-8721-70e4abea9765</semantic:outgoing>
        </semantic:parallelGateway>
        <semantic:callActivity calledElement="" completionQuantity="1" isForCompensation="false" startQuantity="1" name="Call Activity calling a Global User Task " id="_a74c1d4d-db90-43ff-8920-139a300b39a5">
            <semantic:incoming>_be19c2da-316a-47f6-ad7b-eb6c82bf8609</semantic:incoming>
            <semantic:outgoing>_ce63770e-9f4b-4bc0-a56c-88401c59f0bf</semantic:outgoing>
        </semantic:callActivity>
        <semantic:subProcess triggeredByEvent="false" completionQuantity="1" isForCompensation="false" startQuantity="1" name="Collapsed Sub- Process 1 Multi- Instances " id="_149a6e1d-0385-4d0f-a90c-c2150a291a67">
            <semantic:incoming>_e0fbb051-0e07-43cc-a8bf-158492541c0f</semantic:incoming>
            <semantic:outgoing>_dbae7e12-67c2-4256-8c50-5811c207ba55</semantic:outgoing>
            <semantic:multiInstanceLoopCharacteristics isSequential="false"/>
        </semantic:subProcess>
        <semantic:dataObjectReference dataObjectRef="DF1372433666499" name="Data Object " id="_aa8c769a-276c-4589-b182-7c7bbd0a9e1e"/>
 ```

**Interpretation:**
* It appears as if linebreaks are transformed to whitespaces by the tool exporting the BPMN files.
* This is a problem for the XPATH test automation, because it cannot find the correct elements anymore.

**Options:**
The following options for resolving this issue are possible:
* Fix the BPMN files by removing all spaces which stem from linebreaks.
E.g., ```"Collapsed Sub- Process 1 Multi- Instances "``` becomes ```"Collapsed Sub-Process 1 Multi-Instances"```.
* Fix the BPMN files by removing all non-trailing spaces which from from linebreaks.
E.g., ```"Collapsed Sub- Process 1 Multi- Instances "``` becomes ```"Collapsed Sub-Process 1 Multi-Instances "```.
3. Adapt the XPATH tool in order to ignore spaces completely.
In this case, the tests will work with strings like ```"CollapsedSub-Process1Multi- Instances"```. The tests will remain unchanged.

title: Syntax Error: Link Events not connected
body:
Reference model B.2.0 contains a catching and a throwing link event that have different names and are therefore disconnected. This is equivalent to having two sequence flows that are not connected and therefore represents a syntactical error.

```xml
        <semantic:intermediateThrowEvent name="Intermediate Event Link Throw" id="_f27040d5-765c-493c-bbe7-9fb6ad04cbdc">
            <semantic:incoming>_78361e03-8ab9-4317-b8f6-2daa90f20f54</semantic:incoming>
            <semantic:linkEventDefinition name="Intermediate Event Link Throw"/>
        </semantic:intermediateThrowEvent>
```

```xml
        <semantic:intermediateCatchEvent parallelMultiple="false" name="Intermediate Event Link Catch" id="_4f5e6e50-d9d0-4f97-959a-d1b8e1e32788">
            <semantic:outgoing>_c9768243-8e1a-4b09-907b-3f27fa831a6e</semantic:outgoing>
            <semantic:linkEventDefinition name="Intermediate Event Link Catch"/>
        </semantic:intermediateCatchEvent>
```

Proposal:
Give both Link Event Definitions the same name.

title: Inconsistency in the use of the 'X' indicator on gateways
body:
On page 290, the BPMN specification recommends that

> A diagram SHOULD be consistent in the use of the “X” internal indicator. That is, a diagram SHOULD NOT have some Gateways with an indicator and other Gateways without an indicator.

As agreed in our last meeting, the reference files B.1.0 and B.2.0 should therefore be changed in order to honour this best practice recommendation.

Displaying the Xs in one of the two diagrams and omitting them in the other will ensure that both cases can still be tested.

                    \<dc:Bounds height="36.27136901041668" width="105.60000000000001" x="535.0503937007874" y="30.061165888492283"/>

title: Incorrect label bounds in reference file A.4.0.bpmn (and others)
body:
The 'width' and 'height' values within the label bounds of lanes seem to be inverted. "Lane 1", for instance, defines a label with 'height="12.80..."  and width="35.59...", hence representing a horizontal rectangle. The label, however, is supposed to be displayed vertically.

According to the Diagram Definition (DD) specification, the size of the rectangular described by the bounds is specified along the x-y axes. The bounds should therefore always be relative to the x-y axes, independently of the label's direction. If the label is depicted vertically, its bounds should also represent a vertical rectangle.

It could be argued whether an additional 'direction' or 'angle' attribute is needed for labels. At least for the moment the direction can be derived from the shape's 'isHorizontal' attribute.

Also see:
Diagram Definition (DD) spec: Bounds, page 9
BPMN spec: BPMNLabel, page 377

title: Missing datastore reference label
body:
On import Yaoqiang ignores the label (name attribute) for datastore reference (expects and uses the name attribute of the dataStore itself). 

According to the relevant section of the spec (p209 and following) both datastore and datastore reference may have a name. If only one has a name I would think that should be used (whichever it is) and if both have a name I suggest that the reference's name should take precedence (or display both but that will likely take up more space than is desireable).

title: B 2.0 Boundary Intermediate Event Interrupting Error has non-consistent definition?
body:
Definition of object "Boundary Intermediate Event Interrupting Error" contains part that we find a bit misleading (since Error event needs to be interrupting and thus cancel activity):

semantic:boundaryEvent attachedToRef="_7e6ccf38-e740-4537-a439-a8e984d066de" cancelActivity="false" parallelMultiple="false" name="Boundary Intermediate Event Interrupting Error" id="_3c56e6dc-bc87-4d98-b499-462c5b741c5a"

wouldn't >>cancelActivity="true"<< be more correct here?

title: B 2.0 gatewayDirection Unspecified instead of Converging?

We have an issue with importing model B 2.0 to ADONIS. Object "Parallel  Gateway 2" is defined as:
semantic:parallelGateway gatewayDirection="Unspecified" name="Parallel  Gateway 2" id="_397c783e-ad6a-4cf3-8266-9b41962c83bd"

while it seems to us it should be:

title: B.2.0 Expanded Call Activities
body:
The Signavio Process Editor has issues when importing the “Expanded Call Acitivity” as Start Event 3, Start Event 4 Conditional, User Task 12 Muti-Inst. Seq., User Task 13 are wrapped by an subprocess element in the XML,

but Boundary Intermediate Event Interrupting Message, End Event 5 Terminate, End Event 4, Service Task 14 are contained in a separated process element reference by an call activity element.

I guess the subprocess element needs to be merged and replaced by the process element.

[DG] We caught that one.  This was a bug with our serialization that was getting lost in some particular cases.  We will correct it and provide a new serialization ASAP.

title: B.1.0 Labels of Associations
body:
The label of the association between “Call Activity Collapsed” and “Text Annotation” is not present in the BPMN 2.0 XML. This makes the import test failing implicitly as labels are missing on association when capturing the canvas.

Correct me if I am wrong, but from my understanding the BPMN 2.0 Spec does not want to have labels put on associations. At least there is no name attribute.

<semantic:association associationDirection="None" sourceRef="_1237e756-d53c-4591-a731-dafffbf0b3f9" targetRef="_4815ea6a-ede2-489b-8b37-2cdb2835b02c" id="_5362a7ef-ce7e-4a91-9c38-66c07b1b5f49"/>

[DG] You are quite correct that “Labels” of “Associations” and “DataAsssociations”  is not possible in BPMN (and cannot be imported in another, just as for the position of labels).  This raises the higher question of “Should test cases be of only what is serializable” also to be put on the agenda for discussion.

title: A.4.0 Multiple waypoints in a line
body:
There are edges in the XML having 3 waypoints in a line (see example below). It actually helped me to detect issues in the import of  Signavio, but is this intended?

 <bpmndi:BPMNEdge bpmnElement="_0020ed6a-6dde-499f-9fda-36c8bde20ec6" id="E1365195429527__0020ed6a-6dde-499f-9fda-36c8bde20ec6">
                <di:waypoint x="842.0" y="400.0"/>
                <di:waypoint x="860.0" y="400.0"/>
                <di:waypoint x="880.0" y="400.0"/>
                <bpmndi:BPMNLabel/>
            </bpmndi:BPMNEdge>


[DG] Honestly, this was not intended, it is a side effect of the default waypoint (re: breakpoints in the segments) of our routing in both our tools.  One could argue that we should filter them out as they do not “add value” to the layout, but it does indeed provide a nice test case and discussion point to be brought up in the agenda.  Should the serialization be as minimal as possible (i.e. optimized) or as long as it is valid everything should go through?.

title: Proposal: Document test results in a standardized way
body:
Dear team,

We agreed upon sharing the result files for each test in files that are named in a standardized way:

* B.1.0-import.{pdf,png}
* B.1.0-export.bpmn
* etc.

Yet many of the test results are not stored in the bpmn or png files:

* Which model elements are not imported / exported correctly?
* What kinds of errors occur?
* Are there constraints of the editor that make it impossible to recreate every aspect of the reference?

Therefore, I'd like to propose using a simple Markdown file for each application.
In this file, all key model elements are stored. For each model elements, the test case results are documented.

Let us exemplify this for the B.1.0 export test of MID Innovator:

* Participant (Pool) -- OK
	* Start Event Timer -- OK
	* Abstract Task 1 -- OK
	* User Task 2 -- OK
	* Service Task 3 -- OK
	* End Event None 1 -- OK
* Lane 2 -- OK
	* Group -- ISSUE: Cannot create a group in editor
	* User Task 5 -- OK
	* Exclusive Gateway Divergence 2 -- OK
	* Collapsed Sub-Process -- ISSUE: Cannot create an collapsed sub process in editor. Instead used an call activity. 
	* Service Task 7 -- OK
		* Data Association 1 -- ISSUE: Cannot assign a name to a data association in editor
			* Data Object -- OK 
		* Data Association 2 -- ISSUE: Cannot assign a name to a data association in editor
			* Data Store Reference -- OK
	* Exclusive Gateway Convergence 2 -- OK
	* End Event Terminate -- OK

That way, we have a much more detailed view on the outcomes of a test case.

The entire file is available here:

[https://raw.github.com/mskurz/bpmn-miwg-test-suite-fork/master/B%20-%20Validate%20that%20tool%20covers%20conformance%20class%20set/MID%20Innovator-11.5.1.30223/README.md](https://raw.github.com/mskurz/bpmn-miwg-test-suite-fork/master/B%20-%20Validate%20that%20tool%20covers%20conformance%20class%20set/MID%20Innovator-11.5.1.30223/README.md)

Any comments?

Best Regards,

Matthias
